04325nmm a2200769Ia 9780520920842DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20232000cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209208427 a10.1525/97805209208422doi  a(DE-B1597)570376  a(OCoLC)1202625105  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aD804.348b.D56 2000eb 7aHIS0100002bisacsh04a940.53/18/00722211 aDiner, Dan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBeyond the Conceivable :bStudies on Germany, Nazism, and the Holocaust /cDan Diner.  aReprint 2020 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2023] 4c©2000  a1 online resource (286 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aWeimar and Now: German Cultural Criticism ;v200 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe major essays of Dan Diner, who is widely read and "ed in Germany and Israel, are finally collected in an English edition. They reflect the author’s belief that the Holocaust transcends traditional patterns of historical understanding and requires an epistemologically distinct approach. One can no longer assume that actors as well as historians are operating in the same conceptual universe, sharing the same criteria of rational discourse. This is particularly true of victims and perpetrators, whose memories shape the distortions of historical narrative in ways often diametrically opposed.The essays are divided into three groups. The first group talks about anti-Semitism in the context of the 1930s and the ideologies that drove the Nazi regime. The second group concentrates on the almost unbelievably different perceptions of the "Final Solution," with particularly illuminating discussions of the Judenrat, or Jewish council. The third group considers the Holocaust as the subject of narrative and historical memory. Diner focuses above all on perspectives: the very notions of rationality and irrationality are seen to be changeable, depending on who is applying them. And because neither rational nor irrational motives can be universally assigned to participants in the Holocaust, Diner proposes, from the perspective of the victims, the idea of the counterrational. His work is directed toward developing a theory of Holocaust historiography and offers, clearly and coherently, the highest level of reflection on these problems.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)vPersonal narrativesxHistory and criticism. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xCauses. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xHistoriography. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xPersonal narrativesxHistory and criticism. 0aMemoryxSocial aspectsxGermany. 0aMemoryxSocial aspectszGermany. 0aNationalismxGermany. 0aNationalismzGermany. 4aEuropean history. 4aGermany. 4aJudaism. 4aarchitecture. 4afilm. 4ahistoriography. 4ahistory of architecture. 4ahistory of art. 4ahistory of the Americas. 4ahistory. 4aidea. 4aphilosophy. 4apolitical philosophy. 4asocial philosophy. 4athe arts. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520920842?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520920842423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520920842/original  aEBA_EMB  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles